name: caleb
culturalSignificance: Caleb is a name of Hebrew origin that appears in the Bible, known for its association with one of the twelve spies sent by Moses to explore the land of Canaan. Caleb is celebrated for his faithfulness and devotion, as he remained loyal to God and was rewarded with the promise of entering the Promised Land.
modernContext: Caleb remains a popular name in English-speaking countries, consistently ranking in the top 100 names for boys in the United States. Its timeless appeal and strong biblical roots contribute to its enduring popularity.
literaryReferences: Caleb is a character in the Bible, specifically in the Book of Numbers, known for his courage and faith.
personality: People named Caleb are often perceived as loyal, trustworthy, and strong-willed. They are seen as natural leaders who are dependable and supportive.
symbolism: The name Caleb symbolizes faithfulness and devotion, often associated with loyalty and courage.
funFact: Caleb is one of the few biblical figures who is said to have entered the Promised Land due to his unwavering faith.

religiousSignificance.significance: Caleb is a biblical figure known for his faithfulness and courage, one of the two spies who brought back a positive report about the Promised Land.
keyStories: Caleb and Joshua were the only two of the twelve spies who believed that the Israelites could conquer Canaan.
religiousSignificance.spiritualMeaning: Caleb represents unwavering faith and trust in divine promises.
religiousSignificance.historicalImpact: Caleb's story has been a source of inspiration for faithfulness and courage in religious teachings.

historicFigures.significance: Caleb Cushing was a prominent American statesman and diplomat who played a key role in U.S.-China relations.
Caleb Strong was an influential political leader in the early United States, serving as a governor and senator.
